  "why": "The CrossASR method is fundamentally designed around an explicit mechanism that leverages multiple models to discover failures. Its core is differential testing, where an input is flagged as a failure for one Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) model if its transcription is incorrect while at least one other ASR model's transcription is correct. This test oracle is inherently a multi-model design for failure discovery. Furthermore, the paper's efficiency improvement, the Failure Probability Predictor (FPP), directly implements the example given in the metric's 'High' value definition. The FPP is a classifier trained on the test case results (successes and failures) from all ASRs under test from previous iterations. It then guides the selection of new texts that are most likely to cause failures in subsequent iterations. This constitutes 'guiding [test case generation] using feedback from surrogate models', where the entire set of ASRs acts as the source of feedback to find inputs that reveal disagreements and thus failures.",
